Local engagement as a counterweight against populism
PARIS – The parties that once dominated Western democracies were shaken to their core.
Many – including in France, Italy, Greece, and the United Kingdom – suffered crushing election defeats.
Others have changed so drastically that only the name remains.
The Republican Party of US President Donald Trump has little in common with that of former President Ronald Reagan.
These developments are similar everywhere in the West.
The leadership of the once-dominant parties oscillates between denial and desperation, while populists are poaching their traditional supporters.
Some refuse to acknowledge a legitimate reason for their defeat and dismiss their supporters as "pitiful" to their opponents, just like Hillary Clinton did shortly before she lost to Trump in 2016; others are too scared by the populist tide to launch a counterattack.
However, neither denial nor complacency will resolve the frozen political situation.
The progressives must reorganize themselves, and this begins with a diagnosis of the shortcomings of the traditional parties.
A part of the problem is that the traditional parties have not recognized the true issues of our time.
Still trapped on the old ideological battlegrounds, they ignored declining social mobility, intensifying environmental crises, increasing geographical inequality, multiculturalism tensions, and other issues that actually matter to voters.
Decades ago, they were the vanguard.
Today, they are alone in the woods, wondering where everyone has gone.
The social sciences might have an answer to why the mainstream has strayed from the path.
The gap between their objective analysis of reality and the policies of governments has widened to a chasm.
In most Western countries, economists have been aware of the increasing disparity in income and other key indicators between some affluent, globalization-benefiting cities and the rest of the country for a long time.
However, it was not until the government of French President Emmanuel Macron did so, that no national head of government had implemented tax cuts based on residence before.
As a result of this policy, 1% of France's GDP is now primarily redistributed to the poorest parts of the country.
The traditional parties could also learn something by listening directly to voters instead of only through the filters of media and opinion institutions.
In 2016, Macron's movement En Marche! launched the largest door-to-door survey in French history.
What voters told the questioners then became the basis of Macron's presidential election campaign.
For example, "La Grande Marche" had collected countless statements from women about harassment more than a year before the revelations about Harvey Weinstein's alleged sexual assaults on women, and Macron promised to address the issue if elected.
At the time, Macron's stance made him the target of jokes from his opponents; however, the laughter from them soon faded with the rise of the #MeToo era.
However, a precise understanding of society alone is not enough.
The traditional parties are also suffering from poor organization.
They have long believed that modern politics should be organized around elections, where activists distribute flyers at intervals and cheer on the candidates.
This was less cynicism than a symptom of an approach that views democracy as a marketplace consisting of state providers (the government) and consumers (the citizens).
According to this view, the sole purpose of a party is to conquer and maintain power.
It is no wonder that citizens and even party members feel ignored between elections.
Despite these weaknesses, established parties had a number of advantages that delayed their collapse.
In recent years, they had a technological edge over less established opponents, and they were the only political actors with organized voter groups that could mobilize people to elections, organize protests, and start petitions.
But this model no longer works.
Citizens today refuse to be mere consumers of state policy.
Along with a higher level of education, came new demands for participation.
Voters want to be treated as political actors with rights of their own, not as pawns in the game of others.
Furthermore, governments are no longer the only providers of political measures.
This is one of the hard lessons we learned in the two years we worked alongside Macron in the Élysée Palace.
The most pressing political challenges of today – climate change, religious extremism, digital upheavals, and gender equality – cannot be solved by national governments alone.
These challenges require deep cultural changes and, in most cases, measures on sub- and supranational levels.
And finally, technology has lowered the barriers to political participation, so that traditional parties can no longer rely on the election bonus and established support networks.
Those who are good with Google, Twitter, and Facebook do not need a century-old party apparatus.
Political movements need to be reorganized accordingly.
The focus should be on concrete actions, not just elections.
The formal administrative structure of a party should serve as an "back office"; the "front office" should be staffed by people on the ground.
At La République En Marche!, we call this local citizen projects.
These can range from literacy classes after school and integration programs for immigrants to cooperative vegetable gardens and digital training for seniors.
In any case, it's about offering solutions tailored to local problems and thereby strengthening the communities.
Such projects should be seen today as indispensable complements to state policy.
In the future, a party's ability to offer meaningful paths for political and civic engagement will be crucial to its attractiveness.
And by daily demonstrating their reform policies "live," the parties have already laid the groundwork for success on election day.
If voters refuse to listen to what is being said, the answer is not to shout louder.
This is the hard lesson that traditional parties have learned.
Only those who demonstrate a commitment to improving people's lives, rather than simply winning elections, can win the people's support.
Reconnecting with voters' concerns therefore goes hand in hand with adapting party organizations.
To offer a successful alternative to populism, we need a progressive politics on the ground.
